    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sanctions Hurt Iraqis</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Anthony Arnove letter says economic sanctions against Iraq are creating humanitarian and political disaster and are in many ways strengthening regime of Saddam Hussein (Aug 8 Thomas L Friedman Op-Ed column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman is right to stress that ''because of United States economic sanctions on Iraq, Saddam Hussein is now more popular than ever on the Arab street'' (column, Aug. 8).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman is right to stress that ''because of United States economic sanctions on Iraq, Saddam Hussein is now more popular than ever on the Arab street'' (column, Aug. 8).</p>
        <p>During my visit to Iraq in March, it was clear that the sanctions are hurting ordinary Iraqis, while the ruling elite remains insulated from their effects.</p>
        <p>In many respects, the sanctions have strengthened the regime. Meanwhile, the economy has been devastated and Iraqis are dying from easily preventable diseases. The sanctions should be lifted now, before this humanitarian and political disaster gets worse.</p>
        <p>ANTHONY ARNOVE  Cambridge, Mass., Aug. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
